You can definitely move your Gemini experience to the terminal, but there are a few "gotchas" regarding the OpenAI compatibility and how billing works.

1. Can you use Gemini via OpenAI?
Yes and No. * The "No": You cannot use an OpenAI API key to access Gemini. They are separate companies with separate billing systems.

The "Yes": You can use an OpenAI-compatible endpoint. Many CLI tools (including OpenCode) allow you to point to a "Base URL." Since Google provides an OpenAI-compatible adapter for its Gemini API, you can configure OpenCode to talk to Gemini as if it were talking to OpenAI.

2. Can you avoid billing/token counting?
If you want the exact same service as the web version (unlimited usage for a flat monthly subscription), the answer is generally no for API-based tools.

Web/App Interface: Usually covered by a flat subscription (Gemini Advanced) with high usage limits.

CLI/API Interface: This uses the Google AI Studio or Vertex AI backends. These operate on a Free Tier (with rate limits and data sharing) or a Pay-as-you-go Tier (where you pay per 1 million tokens).

[!IMPORTANT]

To use Gemini in the terminal for free, you must use a Google AI Studio API Key on the "Free of charge" plan. This gives you a generous quota (e.g., 1,000 requests/day for Flash models), but Google may use your data to improve their models.

3. OpenCode TUI vs. Official Gemini CLI
There is an official Gemini CLI (often called gemini-cli), and it differs significantly from the OpenCode TUI.

Feature	OpenCode TUI	Official Gemini CLI
Primary Focus	Coding Agent. It reads your files, suggests edits, and can execute terminal commands to fix bugs.	General Assistant. It's a "ReAct" agent that can search the web and run local tools, but is more of a "chat-first" utility.
Interface	Full Terminal UI (TUI) with split panes, chat history, and file trees.	Interactive prompt or one-off commands (e.g., gemini "fix my code").
Model Support	Agnostic. Can use Gemini, Claude, GPT-4, or local models (Ollama).	Gemini Only. Deeply optimized for Gemini 2.0/3.0 features.
Complexity	Higher. Requires more setup (configs, provider connections).	Lower. Usually a simple npm install -g @google/gemini-cli and a Google login.
Ecosystem	Strong focus on "vibe coding" and deep repository context.	Supports MCP (Model Context Protocol) to connect to external data/tools.
Summary Recommendation
If you want a dedicated coding partner: Stick with OpenCode. Go to Google AI Studio, get a free API key, and add it to OpenCode using the /connect command. This uses the Free Tier (no billing).

If you want a quick, official Google tool: Try the official Gemini CLI. It is faster for one-off questions and has built-in Google Search grounding that works very well in the terminal.

