Using OpenCode for Gemini in the terminal is a great move for a keyboard-driven workflow. To address your specific goal—using the terminal without the "token counting and billing" anxiety of a standard API—there is a specific way to set this up.

1. Can you use OpenCode without token billing?
By default, most CLI tools use an API Key, which is "pay-as-you-go" (token billing). However, you have two ways to get a "free" or "flat-rate" experience:

The "Free Tier" Loophole: If you get an API key from Google AI Studio, you can use the Free of Charge plan. This gives you a very high quota (e.g., 1,500 requests per day for Gemini 1.5 Flash) without ever entering a credit card. It "counts" tokens for the quota, but it won't "bill" you.

The Subscription Sync (OAuth): There is a community plugin for OpenCode called opencode-gemini-auth. This allows you to log in via OAuth using your existing Google account. If you have a Gemini Advanced subscription ($20/month), this plugin lets OpenCode tap into that subscription's "unlimited" usage rather than using a metered API key.

2. OpenCode TUI vs. Official Gemini CLI
While both live in the terminal, they are built for different types of "work."

Feature	OpenCode TUI	Official Gemini CLI (@google/gemini-cli)
Philosophy	The "Coding Agent." It’s designed to live inside a git repo and do the work for you.	The "Power Assistant." It’s designed to be a faster, smarter version of the web chat.
Best For	Deep coding tasks: "Refactor this whole directory to use hooks."	Rapid lookups: "How do I unzip this file?" or "Review this PR."
Interface	Full-screen TUI (Terminal User Interface). It has panes, file trees, and a chat history window.	Command-line. You usually type a command and get a response, or enter a simple interactive loop.
"Secret Sauce"	LSP Integration. It can "see" your code errors via Language Servers, just like VS Code does.	Google Search Grounding. It can pull real-time info from the web to answer questions about new libraries.
Multi-Model	Can switch between Gemini, Claude, or local models (Ollama) in the same TUI.	Gemini only. Deeply optimized for Gemini-specific features (like 2M token context).
3. Which one should you use?
Use OpenCode if: You want a terminal-based "Cursor" or "Aider" experience. You want the AI to actually write files, run tests, and manage your project.

Use Gemini CLI if: You just want to talk to Gemini without opening a browser. It’s lighter, faster to start, and better at general knowledge because of the built-in Google Search.

How to start with OpenCode + Gemini (Free)
Go to Google AI Studio and create a Free API Key.

Open your terminal and run opencode.

Type /connect and select Google.

Paste your API key.

As long as you are on the Free tier in AI Studio, you can use it all day without a bill. Just be aware that on the free tier, Google may use your data to train their models (the same way they do on the free web version).





